{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01DifFDYLBjjrwAUfn2gUTtM","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the task. I need to:\n1. Create an openssl-toolbox pod (or use another method to generate certificates)\n2. Generate TLS certificates for CockroachDB\n3. Store the certificates in a Kubernetes secret\n4. Update the CockroachDB StatefulSet to use the certificates (removing `--insecure` and adding `--certs-dir`)\n5. The pods need to mount the certificates\n\nThe goal is:\n1. Insecure access (`--insecure`) is rejected\n2. Secure access with `--certs-dir=/cockroach/cockroach-certs` succeeds\n\nSo I need to generate a CA certificate and node certificates for each CockroachDB instance, create Kubernetes secrets to store them, then update the StatefulSet to mount those secrets and switch from insecure to secure mode, including updating the health check probes to use HTTPS instead of HTTP.\n\nFor the certificate structure in the mounted directory, I need the CA certificate, a node certificate with private key for each node (including all the pod addresses as SANs), and a client certificate for the root user.\n\nFor a multi-node Kubernetes setup, I can either use individual certificates per node or a single shared node certificate with all addresses as SANs—the simpler approach is the latter. I'll need to generate these certificates using either the `cockroach cert` command or openssl, then create Kubernetes secrets from them and update the StatefulSet. Since I need the cockroach binary to generate certs, I could either install it locally or exec into an existing pod to run the cert generation commands.\n\nI'm leaning toward using openssl directly on the host since it's more straightforward and self-contained. CockroachDB uses standard X.509 certificates with specific requirements: a CA cert that signs both node and client certs, node certificates with SANs for all DNS names and IPs, and client certificates with a CN matching the username. Let me verify openssl is available on the host first.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":754,"cache_read_input_tokens":31654,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":754},"output_tokens":33,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9a2cfedd-deef-4b4c-b890-670b3d27cbd9","uuid":"53c829a2-41d6-4d3f-9a13-03c6af03878d","request_id":"req_011Ccb4bUJxKzkR1cntsHZLo"}
