{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01D5jJuaJsnNgg6szFMm8WB3","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I'll use `cockroach cert` command to generate certificates. I can do this by:\n1. Creating a temp directory on the host\n2. Using a cockroach binary from inside one of the pods (via exec with a shared temp dir)\n\nOr alternatively, I can use the cockroach binary from one of the pods by:\n1. Exec into the pod and generate certs there\n2. Copy them out with `kubectl cp`\n3. Create Kubernetes secrets\n\nLet me use the `cockroach cert` commands inside a pod to generate the certs.\n\nHere's the plan:\n\n1. Exec into `crdb-cluster-0` and generate certs in a temp directory\n2. Copy the generated certificates back to the host, then create Kubernetes secrets to store both the node certificates and client root certificates\n3. Modify the StatefulSet to disable insecure mode, point to the certificate directory, mount the secret volume, and update the health checks to use HTTPS\n4. Let the rolling update finish and then verify that secure connections work while insecure ones are rejected\n5. The node certificates need to include SANs for localhost, 127.0.0.1, and the pod DNS names across all three replicas plus the service DNS names\n6. I'll generate the certificates by running the cockroach cert commands, either directly in a pod or from the host using kubectl exec\n7. Then copy the generated certs out with kubectl cp and create Kubernetes secrets from them\n8. Finally update the StatefulSet to mount those secrets and configure TLS","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1630,"cache_read_input_tokens":32408,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1630},"output_tokens":22,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"pare