{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01UefKM3wac3km3W2USt8nwv","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The pods are running in secure mode (TLS) but the readiness probe is failing with HTTP 503. The 503 error likely means the node is running but not yet \"ready\" (not joined the cluster properly).\n\nThe warning says \"The server appears to be unable to contact the other nodes in the cluster.\" This could be because:\n1. The nodes are trying to communicate with each other but the TLS configuration isn't working properly (the node cert is shared across all nodes but uses the same cert for all - that's actually fine for CockroachDB)\n2. The old insecure nodes can't communicate with the new secure nodes during rolling upgrade\n3. This is a rolling update where the first node successfully transitioned to secure mode, but the subsequent nodes can't join because they're still initializing in secure mode while the cluster expects them to be ready. The readiness probe returns 503 specifically when a node hasn't joined the cluster yet.\n\nI'm wondering if the issue is that switching from insecure to secure mode mid-cluster requires all nodes to restart together rather than rolling one at a time. The \"unable to contact other nodes\" warning suggests either a certificate mismatch or a cluster ID problem preventing the nodes from forming a cohesive cluster.\n\nLooking at the logs more carefully, the CockroachDB process is starting with TLS enabled, but the readiness probe is returning 503 because the node hasn't joined the cluster quorum yet. This is normal during startup. The real question is whether the HTTPS readiness probe can actually communicate with the node's TLS-enabled admin interface, or if there's a certificate validation issue preventing the kubelet from reaching it.\n\nWhat's concerning is that crdb-cluster-0 is 1/1 Ready while crdb-cluster-1 and crdb-cluster-2 are still 0/1 after their updates. This suggests the other nodes might be stuck trying to join the cluster, possibly because they can't communicate with the first node over TLS or there's a quorum issue during the rolling restart. The rolling update is probably stalled because crdb-cluster-1 and crdb-cluster-2 aren't ready yet, so crdb-cluster-0 hasn't been touched. That means crdb-cluster-0 is still running the old insecure configuration while the newer pods are stuck trying to come up with TLS enabled, which is why they're returning 503 errors.\n\nThe real issue is that CockroachDB can't transition from insecure to secure mode with a rolling update while keeping the cluster alive—the nodes in different modes can't communicate with each other. To fix this, I'd need to either restart all three pods at once or scale down to zero and back up. nodes to transition to secure mode together. Scaling to 0 and back up would force a simultaneous restart where all nodes come up with TLS enabled and can communicate with each other, even though they're recovering from existing data. TLS mode at the same time. Let me delete pod crdb-cluster-0 to force it to be recreated with the new TLS configuration. I'm checking the StatefulSet's update strategy to understand how the rolling update is progressing—with partition set to 0, all pods should be updated, but the RollingUpdate strategy waits for each pod to be ready before moving to the next, which might be blocking pod 0 from being updated since pods 1 and 2 aren't ready yet.\n\nLooking at the pod ages, I can see the StatefulSet rolled out from highest ordinal to lowest: crdb-cluster-2 was updated first (10m old, TLS config), then crdb-cluster-1 (20m old), while crdb-cluster-0 (46m old) hasn't been updated yet and is still running the non-TLS configuration.\n\nThe rolling update is stuck because pods 1 and 2 can't become ready in TLS mode while pod 0 is still insecure and blocking them from joining the cluster. The simplest fix would be to scale down or delete the problematic pods to force a restart, or manually update pod 0's configuration to match the new TLS spec. Scaling to zero will delete all pods, then scaling back to three will recreate them fresh with the TLS configuration, allowing them to start in secure mode simultaneously. I'm concerned about the data directories on the PVCs containing cluster metadata from the insecure cluster, but since TLS is just a transport layer and doesn't affect the data format, restarting in secure mode with the same persistent data should work fine. The real problem is avoiding the mixed-mode transition, so I'll proceed with the scale-down and scale-up approach.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1403,"cache_read_input_tokens":39934,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1403},"output_tokens":26,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9a2cfedd-deef-4b4c-b890-670b3d27cbd9","uuid":"d03ebab1-c388-4674-b829-2274e56bf663","request_id":"req_011Ccb5ftgdaYDKJgzxUSz6A"}
